Custom properties (often called "CSS variables") hold a value you can reuse with `var()`. Unlike
Sass variables, they're **live in the browser** — they cascade, inherit, and can change at runtime.

## Declaring and using

```css
:root {
  --brand: #6b2fb3;
  --space: 1rem;
}

.button {
  background: var(--brand);
  padding: var(--space);
}
```

## Fallback values

```css
color: var(--accent, currentColor);   /* use currentColor if --accent is unset */
```

## They cascade and scope to elements

A custom property is scoped to the element it's declared on and inherits to descendants —
so you can **override per component or per state**:

```css
.card        { --pad: 1rem; padding: var(--pad); }
.card--roomy { --pad: 2rem; }            /* same rule, new value */
```

## Theming with one switch

Because they're live, flipping a value re-themes everything that uses it:

```css
:root        { --bg: #fff; --fg: #1c1c28; }
[data-theme="dark"] { --bg: #14141c; --fg: #e8e8f2; }

body { background: var(--bg); color: var(--fg); }
```

<Callout type="note">This site's light/dark toggle is exactly this: it flips `data-theme` on `<html>`, and every `var(--…)` updates instantly — no extra CSS per component.</Callout>

Same component, re-themed by overriding the custom properties on a class — edit the values live:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="card">
  <h3>Card</h3>
  <button>Action</button>
</div>
<div class="card card--dark">
  <h3>Same card</h3>
  <button>Action</button>
</div>`}
  css={`.card {
  --brand: #6b2fb3;
  --bg: #f3f0f8;
  --fg: #1c1c28;
  background: var(--bg); color: var(--fg);
  padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; margin: .5rem 0;
}
.card button { background: var(--brand); color: #fff; border: 0; padding: .4rem .8rem; border-radius: 6px; }
.card--dark { --bg: #14141c; --fg: #e8e8f2; --brand: #b794ec; }`}
/>

<Callout type="do">Expose component "knobs" as custom properties (`--gap`, `--columns`). It makes components themeable and overridable without touching their internals.</Callout>

Responsive design delivers a layout that adapts to screen size, platform, and orientation. The core
tool is the **media query** — a block of CSS that only applies when the viewport (or device) matches
a condition.

## Anatomy of a media query

```css
.grid { display: block; }

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }
}
```

A media query is a **media type** (`screen`, `print`, `all` — `screen` is implied) plus one or more
**feature conditions** in parentheses (`min-width`, `orientation`, …). When it matches, the rules
inside apply; otherwise they're ignored.

## Mobile-first (`min-width`)

Style the mobile layout first, then *add* changes upward with `min-width`:

```css
.nav { flex-direction: column; }          /* mobile default */

@media (min-width: 900px) {
  .nav { flex-direction: row; }            /* enhancement for wider screens */
}
```

- Mobile is the most-used platform.
- Mobile styles tend to be simpler, so they make a cleaner base.
- You only layer on complexity where there's room for it.

## `min-width` vs `max-width`

- **`min-width`** → mobile-first; you *enhance upward*. This is the recommended default.
- **`max-width`** → desktop-first; you *override downward*.

```css
/* desktop-first: base is the wide layout, then walk it back */
.sidebar { width: 320px; }
@media (max-width: 700px) {
  .sidebar { width: 100%; }
}
```

<Callout type="warn">Don't freely mix `min-` and `max-width` for the same component — overlapping ranges make it hard to reason about which rule wins. Pick one direction (usually mobile-first) and stay consistent.</Callout>

## Choosing breakpoints

Common starting points — but pick breakpoints where **your content** breaks, not for specific devices:

| Breakpoint | Typical target |
|---|---|
| `≥ 480px` | large phones |
| `≥ 768px` | tablets |
| `≥ 1024px` | small laptops |
| `≥ 1280px` | desktops |

<Callout type="do">Before reaching for a media query, see how far the layout gets with intrinsic sizing (Flexbox/Grid, `min()`/`max()`/`clamp()`, `flex-wrap`). The best breakpoint is often *no* breakpoint.</Callout>

## Combining conditions

```css
@media (min-width: 600px) and (max-width: 900px) { … }   /* both must match  */
@media (min-width: 600px), print { … }                   /* either (OR)      */
@media not all and (min-width: 600px) { … }              /* negate           */
```

## Modern range syntax

Newer, more readable comparison syntax (widely supported):

```css
@media (width >= 768px) { … }
@media (400px <= width <= 900px) { … }   /* an explicit range */
```

## Beyond width: other useful features

```css
@media (orientation: landscape) { … }
@media print { nav, .ads { display: none; } }   /* print stylesheet */
@media (min-resolution: 2dppx) { … }            /* retina / hi-dpi */
```

## Responding to user preferences

These accessibility-focused media features react to OS settings — use them, they're easy wins:

```css
/* respect users who asked for less motion */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * { animation: none !important; transition: none !important; }
}

/* honour the OS light/dark choice */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  :root { --bg: #14141c; --fg: #e8e8f2; }
}
```

<Callout type="note">`prefers-reduced-motion` and `prefers-color-scheme` cost almost nothing to add and make a real difference — reduced-motion prevents nausea/vestibular issues, and respecting dark mode is increasingly expected.</Callout>

## Try it — cross a breakpoint live

**Drag the preview's right edge** to resize the viewport and watch the grid switch from one column
to two as it crosses `min-width: 420px` — a real media query, no JavaScript:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="grid">
  <div class="box">1</div>
  <div class="box">2</div>
  <div class="box">3</div>
  <div class="box">4</div>
</div>`}
  css={`.grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr;     /* mobile default: one column */
  gap: 1rem;
}
.box {
  padding: 1.5rem;
  background: #6b2fb3;
  color: #fff;
  border-radius: 8px;
  font-weight: 700;
  text-align: center;
}
@media (min-width: 420px) {
  .grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; }   /* two columns when wide enough */
}`}
/>

Two modern layout systems. Rule of thumb: **Flexbox for one dimension** (a row or a column),
**Grid for two dimensions** (rows *and* columns).

## Flexbox

A flex container distributes space among its items along a **main axis**, with alignment on the
**cross axis**.

```css
.toolbar {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;        /* main axis = horizontal */
  justify-content: space-between;  /* along main axis   */
  align-items: center;             /* along cross axis  */
  gap: 1rem;
}
.toolbar .spacer { flex: 1; }       /* grow to fill      */
```

**Terminology:** flex container · flex items · flex-direction · main axis · cross axis.

### Play with every flex property

Toggle each property below and watch the boxes rearrange. The generated CSS updates live, so you
can connect each value to its effect — try `flex-direction: column` with different `align-items`, or
add `items` until `flex-wrap: wrap` kicks in.

<LayoutLab mode="flex" />

<Callout type="note">`align-items` aligns on the **cross axis** — so with `flex-direction: row` it moves items up/down, but with `column` it moves them left/right. Watch the boxes flip behaviour when you change direction. (`baseline` lines up the items' text baselines — that's why the boxes have different text sizes.)</Callout>

### A real-world example

Now the same properties on something concrete — change `justify-content`, `gap`, or `flex-direction`:

<Playground
  html={`<div class="toolbar">
  <span>Logo</span>
  <span class="spacer"></span>
  <button>Login</button>
</div>`}
  css={`.toolbar {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 1rem;
  padding: .75rem 1rem;
  background: #f0ebf6;
  border-radius: 8px;
}
.spacer { flex: 1; }            /* pushes the button to the right */
button {
  border: 0;
  padding: .5rem 1rem;
  border-radius: 6px;
  background: #6b2fb3;
  color: #fff;
}`}
/>

## CSS Grid

Grid lays out items into a 2-D grid of **tracks** (rows/columns) and **areas**.

```css
.layout {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;   /* sidebar + fluid content */
  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;
  gap: 1.5rem;
}
```

**Terminology:** grid container · grid items · grid line · grid cell · grid track · grid area.

### Play with grid layout

Pick a preset for `grid-template-columns` / `grid-template-rows` — or **type your own** value in the
field — and watch the boxes flow into the tracks. `justify-items`/`align-items` position each item
*inside* its cell; `justify-content`/`align-content` position the whole grid *within* the container;
`grid-auto-flow` controls the direction items are placed.

<LayoutLab mode="grid" />

<Callout type="note">Two things worth noticing as you experiment: `repeat(auto-fit, minmax(60px, 1fr))` reflows the column count on its own (no media query — the pattern behind the card grid below). And `justify-content`/`align-content` only have a visible effect when the tracks **don't fill** the container — try fixed columns like `repeat(3, 80px)` to see them move the whole grid.</Callout>

## New units, functions & keywords

| | Examples |
|---|---|
| **Units** | `fr` (fraction of free space) |
| **Functions** | `minmax(200px, 1fr)`, `repeat(3, 1fr)`, `fit-content(300px)` |
| **Sizing keywords** | `min-content`, `max-content` |

```css
.cards {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
}
```

<Callout type="do">`repeat(auto-fit, minmax(…, 1fr))` gives you a responsive card grid with **no media queries** — it fits as many columns as will hold the minimum width, then stretches them.</Callout>

<Callout type="note">Use `gap` for spacing instead of margins on items — it works in both Flexbox and Grid and never adds an edge gap.</Callout>

Let the browser interpolate the in-between states when something changes — no JS needed.

## Transitions

A transition animates a property *when its value changes* (e.g. on `:hover`).

```css
.button {
  background: var(--brand);
  transition: background 200ms ease, transform 200ms ease;
}
.button:hover {
  background: var(--accent);
  transform: translateY(-2px);
}
```

The longhands: `transition-property`, `transition-duration`, `transition-delay`,
`transition-timing-function` — or the `transition` shorthand.

## Animations

For multi-step or looping motion, define `@keyframes` and attach with `animation`.

```css
@keyframes fade-in {
  from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(8px); }
  to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
}

.card {
  animation: fade-in 400ms ease both;
}
```

Animation longhands you'll use: `animation-name`, `animation-duration`, `animation-delay`,
`animation-iteration-count`, `animation-direction`, `animation-timing-function`,
`animation-fill-mode` — or the `animation` shorthand.

## Performance

<Callout type="warn">Not every property is animatable, and some are **expensive**. Animating `width`, `height`, `top`, or `left` triggers layout on every frame.</Callout>

<Callout type="do">Prefer animating `transform` and `opacity` — the browser can composite them on the GPU without re-laying-out the page. And respect `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` for accessibility.</Callout>

```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  *, *::before, *::after { animation: none !important; transition: none !important; }
}
```

Hover the button (transition) and watch the badge (keyframe animation) — tweak the timings:

<Playground
  html={`<button class="btn">Hover me</button>
<span class="badge">live</span>`}
  css={`.btn {
  padding: .6rem 1rem; border: 0; border-radius: 6px;
  background: #6b2fb3; color: #fff; cursor: pointer;
  transition: transform .2s ease, background .2s ease;
}
.btn:hover { transform: translateY(-3px); background: #9b6dd6; }

@keyframes pulse { from { opacity: .35 } to { opacity: 1 } }
.badge {
  display: inline-block; margin-left: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #6b2fb3;
  animation: pulse 1s ease-in-out infinite alternate;
}`}
/>

Two modern tools for *controlling the cascade itself* — so specificity wars and source order
stop deciding your styles for you.

## Cascade layers — `@layer`

`@layer` lets you define explicit, ordered buckets. **Layer order beats specificity**: a rule in
a later layer wins over a rule in an earlier layer, *even if the earlier one is more specific*.

```css
@layer reset, base, components, utilities;   /* declare order once */

@layer base {
  a { color: blue; }
}
@layer components {
  .link { color: rebeccapurple; }   /* wins over base, regardless of specificity */
}
```

<Callout type="do">Put third-party/reset CSS in an early layer and your own styles in a later one. You can then override a library with a *simple* class instead of escalating specificity or using `!important`.</Callout>

- Unlayered styles count as the **highest** layer (they win over layered styles).
- `@layer name { }` adds to a layer; re-using the name appends to it.

## Scoped styles — `@scope`

`@scope` limits where rules apply, with a root and an optional lower boundary — useful for
component styling without leaking out.

```css
@scope (.card) to (.card__content) {
  /* applies inside .card, but NOT past a .card__content boundary */
  img { border-radius: 8px; }
  a   { color: var(--brand); }
}
```

- The first parenthesis is the **scope root**; the `to (…)` is the **scope limit** (a "donut").
- Proximity matters: in `@scope`, the closest-scoped rule wins on ties.

See layer order beat specificity — the later layer wins even though the other selector is more
specific. Reorder the `@layer` line and watch the colour flip:

<Playground
  html={`<p class="note">Layer order beats specificity.</p>`}
  css={`@layer base, theme;

@layer theme {
  p { color: rebeccapurple; }   /* later layer */
}
@layer base {
  .note { color: gray; }        /* earlier layer, MORE specific — yet loses */
}`}
/>

<Callout type="note">Layers and scope reduce the need for deeply-nested selectors and `!important`. With BEM keeping specificity flat and layers keeping order explicit, the cascade becomes something you *design* rather than fight.</Callout>

Interactivity is built on **events** — code that listens for activity and runs in response.

<Callout type="note">**In the example** (`assignment/js-starter-accordion`): `accordion.clientlibs.js` `[05]` — one delegated `click` listener on the root, not one per header.</Callout>

## Listening for an event

Pick a target, name the event, give it a callback:

```js
window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
  // do something on resize
});
```

Pass the **event object** to inspect what happened:

```js
button.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
  console.log(event.target);   // the element that was clicked
});
```

## 🛠 Practice — a button listener

Add a click listener to `.my-component__button` that logs `"button clicked"`:

<Reveal>

```js
init() {
  const button = this.element.querySelector('.my-component__button');
  button.addEventListener('click', () => console.log('button clicked'));
}
```

</Reveal>

A working version — click the button and watch the DOM update live:

<Playground
  html={`<button class="btn">Click me</button>
<p class="count">0 clicks</p>`}
  css={`.btn { padding: .5rem 1rem; border: 0; border-radius: 6px; background: #6b2fb3; color: #fff; cursor: pointer; }
.count { font-weight: 700; }`}
  js={`let n = 0;
const btn = document.querySelector('.btn');
const out = document.querySelector('.count');
btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
  n++;
  out.textContent = n + (n === 1 ? ' click' : ' clicks');
});`}
/>

## The three phases

An event travels in three phases: **capturing** (top → target), **targeting** (the element
itself), then **bubbling** (target → up the ancestors). Bubbling is what makes delegation possible.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  C["1 · Capturing<br/>window → target"] --> T["2 · Targeting<br/>the element itself"]
  T --> B["3 · Bubbling<br/>target → ancestors"]
  B --> D["Event delegation listens here"]
```

## Event delegation

Instead of a listener on every child, add **one** listener to a parent and decide what to do from
`event.target`. Efficient, and it works for elements added later.

```js
list.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
  const item = event.target.closest('li');
  if (!item) return;                 // ignore clicks outside an <li>
  alert(item.dataset.info);
});
```

<Callout type="do">Use delegation for lists and repeated items: one listener on the container beats N listeners on the children, and it keeps working when items are added/removed.</Callout>

## 🛠 Practice — delegated list

One `click` listener on the list; if an `<li>` was clicked, alert its `data-info`:

<Reveal>

```js
init() {
  this.element.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    const li = event.target.closest('li');
    if (li) alert(li.dataset.info);
  });
}
```

</Reveal>

<Callout type="note">`event.target` is what was actually clicked; `event.currentTarget` is the element the listener is attached to. `closest()` walks up from the target to find the element you care about.</Callout>

Custom events let **independent components talk to each other** without direct references — one
dispatches, any number listen.

<Callout type="note">**In the example** (`assignment/js-starter-accordion`): `accordion.clientlibs.js` `[06]` — dispatching the `accordion:toggle` event via the shared `emit` helper.</Callout>

<Callout type="when">**When to use it** — to decouple components that shouldn't know about each other: a filter telling unrelated result lists to refresh, a global "close all menus" broadcast, or an "add to cart" signal many widgets react to. For a direct parent↔child relationship, a plain method call or callback is simpler — reach for custom events when a direct reference would create tight coupling.</Callout>

## Create, listen, dispatch

```js
const event = new Event('customEvent');

window.addEventListener('customEvent', () => {
  // react to it
});

window.dispatchEvent(event);
```

You can dispatch on `window`, `document`, or any element. Use a shared target (like `window`) for
broadcast-style communication between unrelated components.

## Carrying data — `CustomEvent`

```js
const event = new CustomEvent('cart:add', { detail: { id: 42, qty: 1 } });
window.dispatchEvent(event);

window.addEventListener('cart:add', (e) => {
  console.log(e.detail.id, e.detail.qty);   // 42 1
});
```

<Callout type="do">Namespace event names (`cart:add`, `lightbulb:on`) so they read clearly and don't collide with native events.</Callout>

## 🛠 Practice — synchronised light bulbs

Several "light bulb" components on the page. Two buttons should switch **all** bulbs on/off via
custom events dispatched on `window`; each bulb toggles `light-bulb__base--on` in response.

<Reveal>

<Tabs>
<Tab label="Code">

```js
// buttons dispatch
onButton.addEventListener('click', () => window.dispatchEvent(new Event('bulb:on')));
offButton.addEventListener('click', () => window.dispatchEvent(new Event('bulb:off')));

// each bulb listens
init() {
  window.addEventListener('bulb:on',  () => this.element.classList.add('light-bulb__base--on'));
  window.addEventListener('bulb:off', () => this.element.classList.remove('light-bulb__base--on'));
}
```

</Tab>
<Tab label="Result">

Clicking **On** dispatches `bulb:on`, and **every** bulb on the page (not just one) adds
`light-bulb__base--on` and lights up — that's the broadcast decoupling. **Off** removes it from all.

</Tab>
</Tabs>

</Reveal>

A working version — both bulbs react to the **same** broadcast event:

<Playground
  html={`<button class="on">All on</button>
<button class="off">All off</button>
<div class="bulbs">
  <span class="bulb">💡</span>
  <span class="bulb">💡</span>
  <span class="bulb">💡</span>
</div>`}
  css={`button { margin-right: .4rem; padding: .4rem .8rem; cursor: pointer; }
.bulbs { margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 2rem; }
.bulb { filter: grayscale(1) opacity(.35); }
.bulb.on { filter: none; }`}
  js={`document.querySelector('.on').addEventListener('click',
  () => window.dispatchEvent(new Event('bulb:on')));
document.querySelector('.off').addEventListener('click',
  () => window.dispatchEvent(new Event('bulb:off')));

document.querySelectorAll('.bulb').forEach((bulb) => {
  window.addEventListener('bulb:on',  () => bulb.classList.add('on'));
  window.addEventListener('bulb:off', () => bulb.classList.remove('on'));
});`}
/>

<Callout type="note">Custom events keep components **loosely coupled** — a component announces *what happened* and never needs to know who's listening.</Callout>

Component JS runs on every page that uses the component, so small inefficiencies multiply. These
patterns keep the front end fast (and tie directly into the Web Performance track).

<Callout type="note">**In the example** (`assignment/js-starter-accordion`): `accordion.clientlibs.js` `[10]` + `accordion.html` show `data-nc-loading="lazy"` and the `import()` pattern. Debounce/throttle and IntersectionObserver are shown as snippets below — the Accordion itself doesn't need them.</Callout>

## Lazy-initialise with IntersectionObserver

Don't do expensive work for components far below the fold. Defer until they're near the viewport:

```js
init() {
  const io = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
    entries.forEach((entry) => {
      if (entry.isIntersecting) { this.start(); io.disconnect(); }  // run once when visible
    });
  });
  io.observe(this.element);
}
start() {
  // heavy work: build a carousel, fetch data, init a map…
}
```

This is also how a **lazy-loading image** component works: create the `<img>` and set its `src`
only once the element intersects the viewport — and reserve space with an aspect-ratio placeholder
to avoid layout shift (CLS).

## Debounce & throttle high-frequency events

`resize`, `scroll`, `input`, and `mousemove` can fire dozens of times a second. Limit the work:

```js
function debounce(fn, wait = 200) {
  let t;
  return (...args) => { clearTimeout(t); t = setTimeout(() => fn(...args), wait); };
}

window.addEventListener('resize', debounce(() => this.recalc(), 200));
```

- **Debounce** — run *after* activity stops (search-as-you-type, resize).
- **Throttle** — run *at most once per interval* (scroll position updates).

<Callout type="do">Add `{ passive: true }` to `scroll`/`touch` listeners so the browser doesn't wait for your handler before scrolling: `el.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true })`.</Callout>

## Dynamic import for heavy/rare code

Don't ship a big dependency in the main bundle if only some pages need it — load it on demand:

```js
async start() {
  const { default: Chart } = await import('./vendor/chart.js');  // separate chunk, fetched now
  new Chart(this.element);
}
```

## Touch the DOM efficiently

- **Cache** queries in `init()` (`this.items = this.element.querySelectorAll(...)`) instead of
  re-querying on every event.
- **Batch** DOM writes; avoid reading a layout property (`offsetWidth`) then writing in a loop
  (layout thrashing). Read first, then write.
- Build markup off-DOM (a `DocumentFragment`) and insert once.

<Callout type="warn">Reading `getBoundingClientRect()`/`offsetHeight` forces the browser to recalculate layout. Doing that inside a loop that also writes styles causes "layout thrashing" — slow, janky frames.</Callout>

<Callout type="note">These map straight onto Core Web Vitals: lazy init and dynamic import protect LCP/INP, aspect-ratio placeholders protect CLS, and passive/debounced listeners keep interactions smooth. See the Web Performance track.</Callout>

## Variables

Declare with `$name: value;` and reuse anywhere.

```scss
$brand: #6b2fb3;
$space: 1rem;

.card { padding: $space; border-color: $brand; }
```

## Data types

| Type | Examples |
|---|---|
| Number | `10`, `10px`, `10.5`, `1rem`, `2em` |
| String | `Netcentric`, `"Netcentric"` |
| Color | `red`, `#ff0000`, `rgba(255,0,0,1)`, `hsl(0, 100%, 50%)` |
| Boolean / Null | `true`, `false`, `null` |
| List | `0 auto`, `Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif` |
| Map | key/value pairs (below) |

### Maps

Keys are unique; values can be any type, including nested lists and maps.

```scss
$theme: (
  brand: #6b2fb3,
  space: 1rem,
  shades: (light: #eee, dark: #222)
);

.box { color: map.get($theme, brand); }   /* helper functions read maps */
```

## Operators

```scss
// Equality
1px == 1px;                 // true
96px == 1in;                // true (unit-aware)

// Boolean
true and true;              // true
not true;                   // false

// Relational
10px < 17px;                // true

// String concatenation
"Helvetica" + " Neue";      // "Helvetica Neue"

// Numeric (unit-aware)
10s + 15s;                  // 25s
1in - 10px;                 // 0.8958...in
100px + 50;                 // 150px
```

<Callout type="warn">Mixing incompatible units throws (`100px < 17s` is an error). And `5px * 3px` gives `15px*px` — multiply a length by a *unitless* number, not by another length.</Callout>

## Interpolation `#{}`

Drop a Sass value into a place that isn't a normal property value — selectors, property *names*,
or inside strings like `calc()`:

```scss
$name: foo;
$attr: border;
$line-height: 30px;

p.#{$name} {
  #{$attr}-color: red;                     /* border-color: red */
  height: calc(100% - #{$line-height});    /* calc(100% - 30px) */
}
```

<Callout type="do">You especially need `#{}` when mixing Sass variables with CSS custom properties or inside `calc()` — Sass won't reach into those without interpolation.</Callout>

