**Jest** is the de-facto test runner for JavaScript front ends. It finds your test files, runs them,
and reports results — batteries included (assertions, mocking, coverage, a DOM environment).

## Anatomy of a test

```js
import { sum } from './math.js';

describe('sum()', () => {
  test('adds two positive numbers', () => {
    expect(sum(2, 3)).toBe(5);
  });

  it('handles negative numbers', () => {   // it() is an alias for test()
    expect(sum(-2, 3)).toBe(1);
  });
});
```

- **`describe(name, fn)`** — groups related tests into a suite (you can nest them).
- **`test(name, fn)`** / **`it(name, fn)`** — a single test case. `it` reads nicely:
  *"it handles negative numbers"*.
- **`expect(value)`** — wraps a value so you can assert on it with a **matcher** (next lesson).

## Running tests

```bash
npx jest                 # run all tests once
npx jest --watch         # re-run on change (only related to git changes)
npx jest math.test.js    # run one file
npx jest -t "negative"   # run tests whose name matches
```

A typical `package.json`:

```json
{
  "scripts": { "test": "jest", "test:watch": "jest --watch" }
}
```

## The lifecycle hooks

Run setup/teardown around tests so each one starts clean:

```js
beforeAll(() => { /* once, before all tests in this file/suite */ });
beforeEach(() => { /* before every test — reset state here */ });
afterEach(() => { /* after every test — clean up */ });
afterAll(() => { /* once, after all tests */ });
```

<Callout type="do">Put shared setup in `beforeEach` so every test is **independent** — tests must pass in any order and never rely on state left by another test.</Callout>

To test a unit in **isolation**, you replace its dependencies (other modules, network, timers) with
**mocks** — fake versions you control and can inspect.

## Mock functions — `jest.fn()`

```js
const onClick = jest.fn();

button.addEventListener('click', onClick);
button.click();

expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.any(Event));
```

Control what a mock returns:

```js
const getUser = jest.fn()
  .mockReturnValue({ name: 'Ada' });        // sync
const fetchUser = jest.fn()
  .mockResolvedValue({ name: 'Ada' });       // resolves a promise
const failing = jest.fn()
  .mockRejectedValue(new Error('boom'));     // rejects
```

## Mocking modules — `jest.mock`

Replace an entire imported module:

```js
import { sendEvent } from './analytics.js';
jest.mock('./analytics.js');   // auto-mock: every export becomes a jest.fn()

test('tracks a click', () => {
  handleClick();
  expect(sendEvent).toHaveBeenCalledWith('cta_click');
});
```

Or provide a custom factory:

```js
jest.mock('./config.js', () => ({ API_BASE: 'https://test.local' }));
```

## Mocking an API (fetch)

```js
beforeEach(() => {
  global.fetch = jest.fn().mockResolvedValue({
    ok: true,
    json: async () => ({ id: 1, name: 'Ada' })
  });
});
afterEach(() => jest.resetAllMocks());

test('loads the user', async () => {
  const user = await loadUser(1);
  expect(fetch).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/api/users/1');
  expect(user.name).toBe('Ada');
});
```

<Callout type="do">Reset mocks between tests — `jest.clearAllMocks()` (clears calls) or `jest.resetAllMocks()` (clears calls *and* implementations) in `afterEach` — so call counts don't leak across tests.</Callout>

<Callout type="warn">Mock at the **boundary** (network, timers, third-party modules), not your own logic. If you mock the very thing you're testing, the test proves nothing. Over-mocking also makes tests brittle and detached from reality.</Callout>

Front-end code is full of async work — fetches, timeouts, animations. The golden rule: **the test
must wait** for the async work, or it passes before the assertion even runs.

## async / await (preferred)

```js
test('loads the user', async () => {
  const user = await loadUser(1);
  expect(user.name).toBe('Ada');
});
```

<Callout type="warn">Forgetting to `await` is the #1 async-test bug: the test finishes and **passes before** the assertion runs. If a test "can't fail", check that you awaited the async call.</Callout>

## `.resolves` / `.rejects`

Assert on a promise's outcome directly:

```js
await expect(loadUser(1)).resolves.toMatchObject({ name: 'Ada' });
await expect(loadUser(0)).rejects.toThrow('not found');
```

## Fake timers

Don't make tests wait real seconds for `setTimeout`/`setInterval` — **fake the clock** and advance it:

```js
test('debounce fires once after 300ms', () => {
  jest.useFakeTimers();
  const fn = jest.fn();
  const debounced = debounce(fn, 300);

  debounced(); debounced(); debounced();
  expect(fn).not.toHaveBeenCalled();

  jest.advanceTimersByTime(300);   // fast-forward
  expect(fn).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);

  jest.useRealTimers();
});
```

Useful timer controls: `jest.advanceTimersByTime(ms)`, `jest.runAllTimers()`,
`jest.runOnlyPendingTimers()`.

<Callout type="do">Use fake timers for anything time-based (debounce, throttle, polling, auto-dismiss). Tests stay **fast and deterministic** instead of sleeping for real.</Callout>

Front-end units often touch the **DOM**. Jest runs them in **jsdom** — a JavaScript implementation
of the browser DOM — so you can create elements, dispatch events, and assert on the result without a
real browser.

## The jsdom environment

```js
/**
 * @jest-environment jsdom
 */
```

Add that comment at the top of a DOM test file, or set it globally in `jest.config.js`:

```js
export default { testEnvironment: 'jsdom' };
```

In jsdom you get `document`, `window`, events, `querySelector`, etc.

## Render markup, then assert

```js
test('renders the label', () => {
  document.body.innerHTML = `
    <button class="cta">Subscribe</button>
  `;
  const button = document.querySelector('.cta');
  expect(button).toHaveTextContent('Subscribe');   // jest-dom matcher
});
```

## Testing events

```js
test('toggles open state on click', () => {
  document.body.innerHTML = `<button class="menu" aria-expanded="false">Menu</button>`;
  const button = document.querySelector('.menu');

  button.addEventListener('click', () => {
    const open = button.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
    button.setAttribute('aria-expanded', String(!open));
  });

  button.click();
  expect(button).toHaveAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
});
```

## Testing a component (the loader pattern)

The JavaScript track's components take an `element` + `options`. That makes them easy to unit-test —
render markup, instantiate the class, assert on the DOM:

```js
import MyComponent from './my-component.js';

test('writes the param text into the element', () => {
  document.body.innerHTML = `<div><span class="my-component__text"></span></div>`;
  const el = document.querySelector('div');

  new MyComponent(el, { text: 'Hello' });

  expect(el.querySelector('.my-component__text')).toHaveTextContent('Hello');
});
```

<Callout type="do">Test what the **user experiences** — visible text, attributes, and behaviour after an interaction — not internal structure. That keeps tests stable when you refactor the markup.</Callout>

<Callout type="warn">jsdom is **not a real browser**: no real layout, no painting, limited support for some APIs (e.g. `getBoundingClientRect` returns zeros). For true rendering/visual behaviour, use an E2E tool (Playwright/Cypress) — that's the top of the pyramid, not unit testing.</Callout>

Tests are code you'll read far more than you write. Keep them **discoverable, consistent, and
readable**.

## Where tests live & how they're named

Two common conventions (Jest finds both by default):

```text
# 1) next to the source (co-located)
src/utils/format.js
src/utils/format.test.js

# 2) in a __tests__ folder
src/utils/__tests__/format.test.js
```

- Use `.test.js` (or `.spec.js`) so Jest picks them up.
- **Co-locating** tests next to the source keeps them visible and easy to update together.

## Structure a suite to mirror the code

Use `describe` per unit, and nested `describe`s per scenario:

```js
describe('formatPrice()', () => {
  describe('with a valid amount', () => {
    it('formats with two decimals', () => { /* … */ });
    it('adds the currency symbol', () => { /* … */ });
  });

  describe('with invalid input', () => {
    it('throws on a negative amount', () => { /* … */ });
  });
});
```

## Write test names as sentences

The name should describe **behaviour**, so a failure reads like a spec:

<Callout type="dont">`test('test1')` · `test('formatPrice works')` — tells you nothing when it fails.</Callout>
<Callout type="do">`it('adds the currency symbol after the amount')` — reads as "formatPrice → with a valid amount → it adds the currency symbol after the amount".</Callout>

## Keep tests DRY — but readable

Factor repeated setup into `beforeEach` or small helpers/factories, but keep each test's **intent**
obvious at a glance:

```js
function makeUser(overrides = {}) {
  return { id: 1, name: 'Ada', active: true, ...overrides };
}

test('inactive users are hidden', () => {
  expect(isVisible(makeUser({ active: false }))).toBe(false);
});
```

<Callout type="warn">Don't over-abstract. A test with so much shared setup that you can't tell what it does is worse than a little duplication. Optimise for **readability over DRY** in tests.</Callout>

